      "acceptanceCriteria": "SQA documentation demonstrates version control, regression testing, and traceability of solver inputs to outputs at Level 2.",
      "rationale": "ANSYS Fluent 2022R2 is used under a validated SQA framework. Version control is maintained via institutional GitLab, regression tests cover all relevant boundary condition types, and solver release notes confirm no outstanding defects affecting rotating machinery hemolysis predictions. SQA Level 2 is achieved."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Numerical code verification",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Code verification demonstrates correct implementation of governing equations for at least one canonical rotating flow problem at Level 2.",
      "rationale": "Order-of-accuracy testing using the method of manufactured solutions was performed for the k-omega SST turbulence model in a rotating reference frame. Observed convergence rates are consistent with second-order spatial accuracy. Code verification is satisfied at Level 2."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Discretization error",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Mesh convergence study with at least three systematically refined meshes and GCI-based discretization error estimate at Level 2.",
      "rationale": "Three structured hexahedral meshes (2.1M, 6.4M, and 18.7M cells) were used. Richardson extrapolation and GCI analysis yield a discretization error of 3.2% on the hemolysis scalar at the finest mesh. This is within the Level 2 threshold for MRL 2 assessments."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Test conditions",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Experimental test conditions must be characterized and matched to simulation boundary conditions with documented uncertainty quantification at Level 3, including fluid property characterization, inlet flow profile measurement, and rotational speed verification traceable to calibrated instrumentation.",
      "rationale": "The in-vitro hemolysis experiments were conducted using a phosphate-buffered saline blood analog at 37°C with viscosity and density measured prior to each test run. Rotational speed was verified using a calibrated optical tachometer (NIST-traceable), and volumetric flow rate was measured with a Coriolis flow meter (±0.5% full-scale accuracy). Inlet velocity profiles were characterized at the pump inlet plane using three-point Pitot traverse measurements, providing sufficient confidence in the mean inlet boundary condition. The assessment team notes that the Pitot traverse method captures only the axisymmetric mean profile and does not resolve inlet turbulence intensity or swirl, which would normally be required for a full Level 3 characterization. However, sensitivity analyses conducted across a plausible range of inlet turbulence intensities (1%–8%) showed less than 4% variation in predicted hemolysis index at the nominal operating point, and prior published experience with this pump family (Morrison et al. 2019; Hariharan et al. 2021) consistently demonstrated that inlet turbulence has negligible influence on impeller-dominated hemolysis predictions. Expert panel review at the 2023 FDA/CDRH workshop on blood-contacting device modeling concurred that for centrifugal pumps at MRL 2, inlet profile sensitivity is a secondary contributor. On this basis, the team considers the test condition characterization to be substantively adequate for the intended decision, and the overall package is recommended for acceptance. The structured Level 3 criterion for full turbulence profile characterization with traceable uncertainty bounds is acknowledged as not formally achieved; the achieved characterization is assessed at Level 2."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Output comparison",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Quantitative comparison of simulation outputs to experimental measurements with reported agreement metrics at Level 2.",
      "rationale": "Predicted relative hemolysis index (RH) agrees with experimental measurements within 12% across all 5 operating points. Pressure rise predictions are within 8% of measured values. PIV velocity comparisons show mean absolute error below 5% of tip speed. All agreement metrics satisfy Level 2 requirements."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the quantities of interest",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "acceptanceCriteria": "The simulation quantities of interest (QoI) are directly linked to the clinical and regulatory decision quantities at Level 2.",
      "rationale": "The primary QoI is the relative hemolysis index (RH), which is the accepted regulatory metric for comparative hemolysis assessment per FDA guidance. The CFD-derived RH is computed from the Giersiepen-Wurzinger power-law model applied to Lagrangian particle tracks, directly corresponding to the experimental normalized index of hemolysis (NIH). Relevance is established at Level 2."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the validation activities to the COU",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Validation activities are performed under conditions sufficiently similar to the COU to support extrapolation of credibility evidence at Level 2.",
      "rationale": "Validation experiments were conducted on the same FDA generic centrifugal blood pump geometry at the same five operating points (flow rates 2–6 L/min, speeds 2000–3500 RPM) specified in the COU. Fluid properties, temperature, and pump configuration match the COU conditions. Validation relevance is at Level 2."
    },
